{
  "query": "What factors influence the survival and growth of canopy algae transplanted onto subtidal artificial structures?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on studies of canopy algae transplantation onto subtidal artificial structures, several key factors influence survival and growth. The survival of canopy algae transplants varied depending on wave-exposure and surrounding habitat, with some studies reporting that no canopy algae transplants survived regardless of protective measures (Action 3471). The presence and mesh size of cages around transplants significantly affected both survival and cover, with two studies finding that canopy algae cover increased and/or was higher when transplanted under cages but decreased and/or was lower when left uncaged (Action 3471). Surface orientation was found to affect growth but had no effect on survival in one study (Action 3471). Wave-exposure influenced the growth of canopy algae transplants, with growth varying depending on this factor and surface orientation (Action 3471). Distance from source populations also played a role, as the abundance of kelp recruits on subtidal artificial structures varied depending on the distance from transplanted kelp individuals (Action 3471). Creating natural rocky reef topography on subtidal artificial structures did not increase the abundance of juvenile canopy macroalgae that settled onto structure surfaces, regardless of topography depth (Action 3446). Surface texture also influenced algae establishment, with textured surfaces having mixed effects on macroalgal abundance depending on the species group and site (Action 3449). Maintenance activities affected algal growth, as reducing the frequency of cleaning on subtidal artificial structures increased macroalgal abundance on structure surfaces (Action 3447).",
