{
  "query": "How do the biodiversity outcomes of creating large hole habitats (>50mm) on artificial structures vary between subtidal zones in Israel and Sweden versus intertidal zones in Australia and Europe?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the available studies, biodiversity outcomes of creating large hole habitats (>50mm) on artificial structures show notable differences between subtidal and intertidal zones across the specified regions.\n\nIn subtidal zones in Israel and Sweden (Action 3434), three studies found that creating hole habitats altered the combined macroalgae and invertebrate or mobile invertebrate and fish community composition on and around structures, and supported mobile invertebrate, non-mobile invertebrate and/or fish species that were absent from structure surfaces without added habitat features. However, biodiversity outcomes were mixed: two of three studies found increased combined macroalgae and invertebrate species richness and/or diversity, while one study found no increase in combined mobile invertebrate and fish species richness or diversity. Population-level effects were generally limited, with one study showing no increase in combined mobile invertebrate and fish abundance, and mixed effects on species-specific abundances depending on the species group.\n\nIn intertidal zones in Australia and Europe (Action 3467), five studies examined hole habitats on artificial structures in southeast Australia, the UK, the Netherlands, and northern Israel. These studies consistently found that hole habitats altered the combined macroalgae and invertebrate community composition on structure surfaces and supported macroalgae and/or non-mobile invertebrate species that were absent from structure surfaces without added habitat features. All three studies examining richness/diversity found that creating hole habitats increased the combined macroalgae and invertebrate species diversity and/or richness on structure surfaces. However, population-level effects were limited, with studies showing no increase in macroalgal abundance and mixed effects on invertebrate abundance. One study in Australia reported that hole habitats were used by sea slugs, urchins and octopuses.\n\nThe key difference appears to be that intertidal hole habitats showed more consistent positive effects on species diversity/richness across studies, while subtidal hole habitats showed more variable outcomes for diversity measures and generally limited population-level effects.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3434",
    "3467"
  ]
}

