{
  "query": "What are the general ecological effects of simultaneously creating grooves and small protrusions, ridges, or ledges on artificial structures?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on studies examining artificial structures in marine environments, creating grooves and small protrusions, ridges, or ledges (1-50 mm) simultaneously produces several ecological effects. On intertidal structures, these features alter the combined macroalgae and invertebrate community composition and support species that are absent from structures without these modifications (action 3474). Six of 11 studies found that creating grooves and small ridges/ledges increased combined macroalgae and invertebrate species diversity and/or richness on structure surfaces, while five studies found mixed effects depending on the depth/height of grooves and ridges, shore level, species group, and site (action 3474). The effects on overall abundance are variable, with studies finding no increase, increases when combined with other features or covers, or mixed effects depending on size, arrangement, shore level, and site (action 3474). For invertebrate abundance specifically, five of seven studies found mixed effects on mobile invertebrate, non-mobile invertebrate, limpet, mussel, juvenile oyster, and barnacle abundances, depending on the depth/height of grooves and ridges, presence of large ledges or water-retaining covers, shore level, and site (action 3474). On subtidal structures, the effects are more limited in scope but similar in nature - one of two studies found that groove habitats and small ledges altered community composition and increased species richness and diversity, while effects on abundance were mixed depending on surface orientation (action 3452). The created features are actively colonized by microalgal species on intertidal structures (action 3474) and by macroalgae and non-mobile invertebrates on subtidal structures (action 3452).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3474",
    "3452"
  ]
}

