{
  "query": "How do the biodiversity outcomes of creating small pits (1-50 mm) versus larger holes (>50 mm) on intertidal artificial structures compare?",
  "relevant_summary": "Twenty-two studies examined small pits (1-50 mm) while five studies examined larger holes (>50 mm) on intertidal artificial structures. For community composition, both small pits and larger holes altered macroalgae and invertebrate community composition and supported species absent from unmodified surfaces (Action 3475, Action 3467). Small pits supported fish species absent from surfaces without pits and altered fish community composition (Action 3475), while no fish community data was reported for larger holes (Action 3467). For species richness and diversity, eight of 12 studies found small pits increased combined macroalgae and invertebrate species richness and/or diversity (Action 3475), while all three studies found larger holes increased species diversity and/or richness (Action 3467). Small pits increased macroalgal species richness, limpet and periwinkle species richness (in some cases), and fish species richness (Action 3475), while larger holes had no specific data on individual taxonomic groups (Action 3467). For abundance outcomes, small pits showed mixed results with two of five studies finding increased combined abundance, while effects varied by species and site (Action 3475). For larger holes, one study found no increase in macroalgal abundance and mixed results for invertebrate abundance depending on shore level and site (Action 3467). Small pits showed varied occupancy by limpets and periwinkles depending on pit characteristics and were used by various species including fish that increased biting behavior (Action 3475). Larger holes were used by sea slugs, urchins and octopuses (Action 3467).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3475",
    "3467"
  ]
}

