{
  "query": "What is the evidence for the effectiveness of reducing the slope of marine artificial structures for biodiversity?",
  "relevant_summary": "The evidence for the effectiveness of reducing the slope of marine artificial structures for biodiversity is very limited. For intertidal artificial structures, two studies in an estuary in southeast Australia examined this intervention (Action 3461). One before-and-after study reported that reducing the slope of an intertidal artificial structure, along with creating rock pools, increased the combined macroalgae, invertebrate and fish species richness on the structure. However, one replicated, controlled study found that reducing the slope of an intertidal artificial structure did not increase macroalgal abundance on structure surfaces and did not increase oyster or mobile invertebrate abundance on structure surfaces (Action 3461). For subtidal artificial structures, no studies were found that evaluated the effects of reducing the slope on biodiversity, meaning there is no evidence to indicate whether the intervention has any desirable or harmful effects (Action 3442).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3461",
    "3442"
  ]
}

