{
  "query": "What interventions have been studied in Singaporean waters to enhance intertidal artificial structures, and what were their outcomes?",
  "relevant_summary": "Several interventions have been studied in Singaporean waters to enhance intertidal artificial structures. Action 3475 reports that six studies were conducted on island coastlines in the Singapore Strait examining the creation of pit habitats (1-50 mm) on intertidal artificial structures. The outcomes showed that creating pit habitats altered the combined macroalgae and invertebrate community composition on structure surfaces and supported macroalgae, invertebrate and fish species that were absent from structure surfaces without added habitats. Action 3475 indicates that creating pit habitats along with grooves increased fish species richness on and around structure surfaces, fish abundance, and the number of bites fishes took from structure surfaces. Action 3473 reports that two studies were conducted on island coastlines in the Singapore Strait examining the creation of groove habitats (1-50 mm). The outcomes showed that groove habitats created along with pits altered the fish community composition on and around structure surfaces, supported species that were absent from surfaces without grooves and pits, increased combined macroalgae and invertebrate species richness and diversity, fish species richness, fish abundance, and the number of bites fishes took from structure surfaces. Action 3462 indicates that two studies were conducted on island coastlines in the Singapore Strait examining small protrusions (1-50 mm) on intertidal artificial structures. The outcomes showed that creating small protrusions along with grooves, small ridges and pits increased the combined macroalgae and invertebrate species richness on structure surfaces, with mixed effects on community composition and abundance depending on site and size/arrangement of features. Action 3471 reports that one study was conducted on an island coastline in the Singapore Strait examining coral transplantation onto subtidal artificial structures. The outcomes showed that transplanting corals increased coral species richness and coral cover on structure surfaces, with survival and growth varying depending on coral species.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3475",
    "3473",
    "3462",
    "3471"
  ]
}

