{
  "query": "What is the state of evidence for creating 'swimthrough' habitats on marine artificial structures?",
  "relevant_summary": "The evidence for creating swimthrough habitats on marine artificial structures is limited but shows mixed results across different studies. For small swimthrough habitats (\u2264100 mm) on subtidal artificial structures, four studies examined effects with mixed outcomes - one study in France found mixed effects on juvenile fish community composition and species richness depending on site and survey month, while swimthrough habitats supported six species absent from surfaces without swimthroughs (Action 3436). Two studies found mixed effects on juvenile fish abundances depending on species, site, survey month and development stage (Action 3436). Three studies reported that small swimthroughs were used by juvenile spiny lobsters, sea firs, adult fish and juvenile fish (Action 3436). For large swimthrough habitats (>100 mm) on subtidal structures, two studies showed more positive results - one study in the USA found that large swimthroughs supported fish species absent from surfaces without swimthroughs, increased overall fish species richness and abundance, though effects varied by fish size class and species (Action 3456). One study in Mayotte reported use by juvenile spiny lobsters, groupers, sea firs and adult fishes from five families (Action 3456). For intertidal structures, evidence is more limited - two studies on small swimthroughs found no effects on mobile invertebrate community composition, species richness or diversity, but did find increased mobile invertebrate abundance and altered invertebrate abundance patterns (Action 3468). For large swimthrough habitats on intertidal structures, no studies were found (Action 3438).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3436",
    "3456",
    "3468",
    "3438"
  ]
}

