{
  "query": "What are the effects of creating flexible habitats on the biodiversity of intertidal artificial structures?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on studies from the Netherlands and Australia, creating flexible habitats on intertidal artificial structures has varied effects on biodiversity. For long flexible habitats (>50 mm), one study in the Netherlands reported that creating these habitats altered the combined macroalgae and non-mobile invertebrate community composition on structure surfaces (Action 3460). The flexible habitats themselves supported macroalgae, mobile and non-mobile invertebrates that were absent from structure surfaces without flexible habitats (Action 3460). For short flexible habitats (1-50 mm), one study in Australia found that creating these habitats altered the combined macroalgae and non-mobile invertebrate community composition on structure surfaces, and had mixed effects on the combined mobile invertebrate and fish community composition on and around structure surfaces during low tide, depending on the site (Action 3459). However, short flexible habitats did not alter mobile invertebrate community composition during high tide or fish community composition during high tide (Action 3459). Short flexible habitats decreased the combined macroalgae, invertebrate and fish species richness during low tide, had mixed effects on mobile invertebrate species richness during high tide depending on the site, and did not increase fish species richness during high tide (Action 3459). Additionally, short flexible habitats had mixed effects on macroalgal abundance and invertebrate abundance depending on species group and site, did not increase fish abundance during high tide, and did not increase fish feeding behavior (Action 3459).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3460",
    "3459"
  ]
}

